<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-power-series" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Power Series</title>

  <xi:include href="sec-power-series-radius.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="sec-calculus-of-power-series.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="sec-analytic-functions.ptx" />
  <xi:include href="sec-taylors-theorem.ptx" />

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      This chapter builds directly on the material on geometric series and
      convergence tests from <xref ref="sec-convergence-tests-for-series"/>
      and on the differentiation results from
      <xref ref="sec-the-mean-value-theorem"/>. For external references,
      compare <xref ref="biblio-lebl-basic-analysis"/>, Sections 2.6 and 4.3,
      <xref ref="biblio-rudin-pma"/>, Chapter 8, and
      <xref ref="biblio-boas-primer"/> for further examples involving smooth
      but non-analytic functions.
    </p>
  </conclusion>

  <exercises xml:id="ex-ch6">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-radius-basic">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the radius of convergence and the interval of convergence of
          each power series.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p><m>\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n}</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty n!x^n</m>,</p></li>
          <li><p><m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-shifted-center">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the radius of convergence and the interval of convergence of
          <md>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(x-2)^n}{3^n}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-sum-n-over-three-power-n">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the geometric series and term-by-term differentiation to compute
          <md>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n}{3^n}.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-log-and-arctan">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Starting from the geometric series, derive the power series for
          <m>\ln(1+x)</m> and <m>\arctan x</m> about <m>0</m>. In each case,
          determine the radius of convergence.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-smooth-not-analytic">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>
            f(x)=\begin{cases}
            e^{-1/x} &amp; \text{if } x&gt;0,\\
            0 &amp; \text{if } x\le 0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          Show that every derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>0</m> is equal to
          <m>0</m>. Conclude that <m>f</m> is not analytic at <m>0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-taylor-ln-error">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>P_3(x)=x-\frac{x^2}{2}+\frac{x^3}{3}</m>, the third Taylor
          polynomial of <m>\ln(1+x)</m> at <m>0</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li><p>Compute <m>\ln(1+x)-P_3(x)</m> in the form given by Taylor's theorem.</p></li>
          <li><p>Use this to show that <m>|\ln(3/2)-P_3(1/2)| \le 1/32</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-power-series-binomial-sqrt">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the binomial series to write down the first four nonzero terms
          of the power series for <m>\sqrt{1+x}</m> about <m>0</m>. What is
          the radius of convergence?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</chapter>
